        <name>19.2.8.2 Solve the equation using the integrating factor</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Using the integrating factors you find, find the general solutions the following equations. Use \(C\) as the arbitary constant.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;

    &lt;li&gt;
        &lt;p&gt;\(x \dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}+{@a@}xy=xe^{-{@a@}x}\), \(y=\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/li&gt;

    &lt;li&gt;
        &lt;p&gt;\(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}-(\tan x)y={@b@}\),  \(y=\) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/li&gt;

&lt;/ol&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;

    &lt;li&gt;
        &lt;p&gt;The standard form is \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}+{@a@}y=e^{-{@a@}x}\) for which the integrating factor is \(e^{{@a@}x}\).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Then, on  multiplying through by \(e^{{@a@}x}\) we have
\[e^{{@a@}x}\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}+{@a@}e^{{@a@}x} y=1\]
i.e.\[\dfrac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}x}\ (e^{{@a@}x}y)  =1\qquad \text{so that }\qquad e^{{@a@}x}y=x+C\]
leading to\[y=(x+C)e^{-{@a@}x}.\]
 &lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/li&gt;

    &lt;li&gt;
        &lt;p&gt;The equation is in standard form and the integrating factor is \(\cos x\).  
Then \[\dfrac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}x}(y\cos x )={@b@}\cos x\quad \text{so that }\quad y\cos x=\int {@b@}\cos x\,\mathrm{d}x= {@b@}\sin x+C\]
giving \[ y={@b@}\tan x+C\sec x\]&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/li&gt;

&lt;/ol&gt;</generalfeedback>
